WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:16.050 --> 00:00:21.510
&gt;&gt; Please welcome to our stage,
Carla Hayden and David Ferriero.

00:00:21.510 --> 00:00:27.510
[ Music ]

00:00:27.510 --> 00:00:42.670
[ Clapping ]

00:00:42.670 --> 00:00:43.970
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Well --

00:00:43.970 --> 00:00:45.680
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero:
How have you been?

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:47.800
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: We call
ourselves partners in crime.

00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:50.170
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: We are
though we're not going to talk

00:00:50.170 --> 00:00:52.290
about the crime part
of it, right?

00:00:52.290 --> 00:00:55.190
[Laughter] We're just going to
talk about the partner part.

00:00:55.190 --> 00:00:58.900
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Well, what's
been really interesting

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:00.700
since I've been in the position

00:01:00.700 --> 00:01:07.790
of Library [inaudible] is the
fact that people ask me well,

00:01:07.790 --> 00:01:09.600
what does the National
Archives do?

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:11.380
You know --

00:01:11.380 --> 00:01:12.680
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero:
What do you mean?

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:13.980
What does that mean?

00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:15.650
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: What
does the archivist do?

00:01:15.650 --> 00:01:17.820
You're the Library of Congress.

00:01:17.820 --> 00:01:23.140
And then this -- there's a
confusion about the histories

00:01:23.140 --> 00:01:26.960
and the roles of each
of the institutions.

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:30.940
And I've learned a lot in that
even about the tank coming

00:01:30.940 --> 00:01:36.390
up to reclaim the
Declaration of Independence,

00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:39.670
the Bill of Rights,
and was there a third?

00:01:39.670 --> 00:01:42.240
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: We
call it the Constitution.

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:44.470
[ Laughter ]

00:01:44.470 --> 00:01:46.700
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: That were
held by the Library of Congress

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:48.000
and that type of thing.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:49.300
So could you --

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:52.350
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Well you got
an earlier start than we did.

00:01:52.350 --> 00:01:54.540
It wasn't until the 1930s

00:01:54.540 --> 00:01:57.870
that the United States got
serious about its record.

00:01:57.870 --> 00:02:01.360
And it was Franklin Roosevelt
who was passionate about records

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:05.490
that we actually created the --

00:02:05.490 --> 00:02:09.690
he signed the legislation that
created the National Archives.

00:02:09.690 --> 00:02:13.540
The charters that Carla
is referring to had been

00:02:13.540 --> 00:02:15.670
in the custody of the
State Department and then

00:02:15.670 --> 00:02:17.260
at the Library of Congress.

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:20.860
And when the Archives
building was built,

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:22.890
a beautiful tabernacle
was created

00:02:22.890 --> 00:02:24.950
for the Declaration
of Independence.

00:02:24.950 --> 00:02:29.700
Doors opened in 1935 but the
librarian of Congress refused

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:32.060
to release the Declaration.

00:02:32.060 --> 00:02:34.100
[ Laughter ]

00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:37.770
And I've held that against
you [laughter] ever since.

00:02:37.770 --> 00:02:39.070
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden:
I wasn't born then

00:02:39.070 --> 00:02:41.510
but I knew this was
going to happen.

00:02:41.510 --> 00:02:43.690
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: And it
wasn't until Harry Truman came

00:02:43.690 --> 00:02:47.180
into office that he, you know,
kind of laid down the law

00:02:47.180 --> 00:02:50.230
with the new librarian of
Congress that they really needed

00:02:50.230 --> 00:02:52.180
to deliver that document
where it belonged.

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:57.880
So as Carla describes it, it
was a really military ceremony

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:02.530
with tanks and military people
lining the steps of the --

00:03:02.530 --> 00:03:06.520
and she claims she always
describes it as a grab

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:09.290
for the Declaration
[laughter] but it --

00:03:09.290 --> 00:03:10.590
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden:
Tanks literally --

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:11.890
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: -- was the
only transfer of the document

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:13.630
to its rightful place.

00:03:13.630 --> 00:03:15.400
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And
we have photographs.

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:16.700
Photographs --

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:18.000
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: We do.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:19.300
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden:
-- of the people.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:22.170
The tanks with the
-- what are those?

00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:23.470
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Howitzers.

00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:25.290
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Yes.

00:03:25.290 --> 00:03:29.060
[Laughter] Right there waiting
and you can imagine the curators

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:33.020
and the librarians thinking
well maybe it's time.

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:35.360
And who was the librarian
of the Congress then?

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:36.660
Do you remember?

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:37.960
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Oh I forget.

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:39.260
Someone here must remember.

00:03:39.260 --> 00:03:40.560
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Someone here.

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:41.860
Winston Tab is here.

00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:43.160
He is my check on all the time.

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:44.460
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Oh Winston.

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:45.760
You were here.

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:47.060
What was the --

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:48.360
[ Laughter ]

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:51.430
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: But that
was the start of the kind

00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:57.010
of clarification of roles and
to really divide up things.

00:03:57.010 --> 00:04:01.340
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: The
Archives was created to collect

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:03.590
and protect and made
available the records

00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:05.020
of the United States government.

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:06.850
So anything that was
created by the government.

00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:09.880
So the question -- the natural
question is what about the stuff

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:14.460
that was created before 1934
when the legislation was signed?

00:04:14.460 --> 00:04:16.140
A lot of it is in our custody.

00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:18.820
Some of it is at the
Library of Congress.

00:04:18.820 --> 00:04:21.770
Since the materials were stored
in attics and basements all

00:04:21.770 --> 00:04:25.370
over town, a lot of it was
lost through the fire and theft

00:04:25.370 --> 00:04:31.040
and flood but what we have
now is a dividing line

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:34.130
between everything
the government creates

00:04:34.130 --> 00:04:38.200
and that's me, and everything
they don't create which is you.

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:40.000
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And
sometimes I like to --

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.220
and there are times when
I'm glad you're you.

00:04:44.680 --> 00:04:45.980
[Laughter] I've learned that.

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:47.350
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: And there are
times when I wish I were you.

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:49.410
[ Laughter ]

00:04:49.410 --> 00:04:53.990
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And I've
described it in another way too

00:04:53.990 --> 00:05:01.620
that for instance, Truman and
his official records might be

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:04.330
with the Truman Library
and I'd really like to get

00:05:04.330 --> 00:05:09.530
into those things too with the
Presidential Libraries and some

00:05:09.530 --> 00:05:12.230
of the letters that he
wrote to his family.

00:05:12.230 --> 00:05:18.240
So the person is where you might
-- the things that the person,

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:21.330
the diaries, all of the things
like that, the personal part

00:05:21.330 --> 00:05:25.260
and the personal life
of an official might be

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:26.740
at the Library of Congress.

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:30.130
And so the papers
of 23 presidents

00:05:30.130 --> 00:05:34.430
from George Washington
to Coolidge are

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:36.460
at the Library of Congress.

00:05:36.460 --> 00:05:39.770
And we were both in
Starkville, Mississippi.

00:05:39.770 --> 00:05:41.230
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero:
Starkville, Mississippi,

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:45.320
where Ulysses S. Grant is still
probably revolving in his grave

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:46.620
through [multiple speakers].

00:05:46.620 --> 00:05:47.920
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And
the Abraham Lincoln.

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:49.220
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Yes.

00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:50.520
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Collection.

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:52.010
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Ulysses S.
Grant Presidential Library --

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:53.470
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden:
Library is in Starkville.

00:05:53.470 --> 00:05:54.770
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero:
At -- in Mississippi.

00:05:54.770 --> 00:05:56.070
Can you believe it?

00:05:56.070 --> 00:05:57.380
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden:
And we were there.

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:58.680
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: We were.

00:05:58.680 --> 00:05:59.980
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And
[multiple speakers].

00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:01.280
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: It
turns out there are more

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:04.190
than 200 Presidential
sites around the country.

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:06.070
People beyond the
Library of Congress

00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:08.640
and the National Archives who
have some kind of responsibility

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:13.340
for some aspect of a President's
life and they're all meeting

00:06:13.340 --> 00:06:16.510
in Washington in August.

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:17.810
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And
what's interesting

00:06:17.810 --> 00:06:19.400
about the Presidential
Libraries,

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:27.080
the Library of Congress has
custody of the actual papers

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:30.710
and documents of Ulysses
S. Grant and what some

00:06:30.710 --> 00:06:35.740
of the Presidential Libraries
do is what they will collect

00:06:35.740 --> 00:06:40.520
and make copies of things
from different collections

00:06:40.520 --> 00:06:42.150
about a President and
put them in [inaudible].

00:06:42.150 --> 00:06:43.450
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero:

00:06:43.450 --> 00:06:44.750
Those Presidential
cites, that's right.

00:06:44.750 --> 00:06:46.050
Yes.

00:06:46.050 --> 00:06:47.350
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Place
and that's how the --

00:06:47.350 --> 00:06:48.920
some of the Presidential
Libraries have --

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:50.220
been established.

00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:51.520
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: So when
Franklin Roosevelt created the

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:54.070
National Archives,
he also decided

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:55.500
to have a Presidential Library.

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:58.050
So technically his
was the first --

00:06:58.050 --> 00:07:01.220
I'm convinced he was
a closet archivist.

00:07:01.220 --> 00:07:02.990
He was really passionate
about his papers

00:07:02.990 --> 00:07:05.280
and understood the
importance of archives.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:08.070
Spent a lot of time hiring the
first archivist and spent a lot

00:07:08.070 --> 00:07:11.110
of time supporting
that first archivist,

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:14.640
Robert Connor [phonetic], in his
work as he was trying to figure

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:17.620
out where the records
are, and more importantly,

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:20.840
to convince the agency heads
to give up their records

00:07:20.840 --> 00:07:22.140
because that wasn't something

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:24.880
that people were
interested in doing.

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:27.960
So Roosevelt created his
own library or Herbert --

00:07:27.960 --> 00:07:30.580
whoever decided he wanted
a library at that point

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:31.880
but this was all voluntary.

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:35.530
It was all voluntary up
until 1972 when thanks

00:07:35.530 --> 00:07:38.900
to President Nixon
and his thoughts

00:07:38.900 --> 00:07:43.070
that he owned his own records
that legislation was passed,

00:07:43.070 --> 00:07:44.370
the Presidential Records Act,

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:46.330
which made it government
property.

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:52.180
So 1972 is kind of our marker
for you have to donate.

00:07:52.180 --> 00:07:55.570
You have to give your papers
to the National Archive.

00:07:55.570 --> 00:07:58.430
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And so the role
really became official then.

00:07:58.430 --> 00:07:59.730
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Yeah.

00:07:59.730 --> 00:08:01.220
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And then
the other departments

00:08:01.220 --> 00:08:05.860
and that's another confusion
that happens sometimes.

00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:07.160
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Well
it's a separate set of laws.

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:09.440
Presidential Records
Act was 1972.

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:12.590
The Federal Records Act was
created much earlier than that.

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:16.160
And that guides all of the
records management activities

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:17.560
for the Executive Branch.

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:22.300
So all of the 275 Executive
Branch Cabinet level

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:24.370
and agencies and departments.

00:08:24.370 --> 00:08:27.290
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: What
about congressional records

00:08:27.290 --> 00:08:28.590
of [multiple speakers] --

00:08:28.590 --> 00:08:29.890
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: We provide

00:08:29.890 --> 00:08:32.890
by a gentleman's
agreement way back when,

00:08:32.890 --> 00:08:35.850
we provide courtesy
storage for the records

00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:38.830
of Congress and service them.

00:08:38.830 --> 00:08:43.360
They are the records of
Congress but they aren't

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:45.680
at the Library of Congress.

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:46.980
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And you --

00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:50.170
and I want all of the people
watching and listening

00:08:50.170 --> 00:08:55.550
to realize that the joy of
working with your colleagues.

00:08:55.550 --> 00:08:56.850
Some that you've known.

00:08:56.850 --> 00:09:01.180
I've known David his time at
New York Public and all of that,

00:09:01.180 --> 00:09:04.400
is that you have this
kind of friendly,

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:08.970
kind of historical
whatever competition.

00:09:08.970 --> 00:09:10.270
[Laughter] So when
you talk about your --

00:09:10.270 --> 00:09:11.570
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero:
And some grudges.

00:09:11.570 --> 00:09:12.870
Still carrying --

00:09:12.870 --> 00:09:14.170
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And grudges.

00:09:14.170 --> 00:09:15.470
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero:
-- some grudges.

00:09:15.470 --> 00:09:16.770
[Laughter]

00:09:16.770 --> 00:09:18.070
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: So
when you talk about

00:09:18.070 --> 00:09:19.370
and I know you've seen that
movie, National Treasure.

00:09:19.370 --> 00:09:20.670
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Yes.

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:21.970
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: You
got all the kids.

00:09:21.970 --> 00:09:23.270
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Yes.

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:24.570
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And they're
doing it but the Library

00:09:24.570 --> 00:09:27.960
of Congress has that
first printing

00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:29.840
that just had John
Hancock on it.

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:31.520
And then they send it out.

00:09:31.520 --> 00:09:32.820
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: It wouldn't
have been that first printing

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:36.780
if those original signors
didn't sign something.

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:38.080
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: See.

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:39.380
[ Laughter ]

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:40.680
And --

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:41.980
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: Which I have.

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:43.280
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: And
David Ferriero --

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:44.580
[laughter] right, right, okay.

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:45.880
It's okay.

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:47.180
It's okay.

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:50.460
And the Gettysburg Address, you
know, that he took on the field.

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:51.760
&gt;&gt; David Ferriero: That's right.

